        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Doubly Linked Lists

            A **doubly linked list** is a linear data structure where:
            - Each node stores **data**
            - A pointer to the **next** node
            - A pointer to the **previous** node

            Traversal is possible **in both directions**.
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Node Structure

            Each node contains three parts:
            - **Data**
            - **Prev** → pointer to previous node
            - **Next** → pointer to next node

            This extra pointer makes navigation more flexible than singly linked lists.
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Visual Representation

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              NULL1((NULL)) <-->|prev| A[A] <-->|next/prev| B[B] <-->|next/prev| C[C] <-->|next| NULL2((NULL))
            /mermaid

            - First node's **prev** is NULL  
            - Last node's **next** is NULL
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Traversal

            You can traverse:
            - **Forward** using `next`
            - **Backward** using `prev`

            This is useful for:
            - Undo/redo operations
            - Navigation systems
            - Browsing history
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Insertion at the Beginning

            Steps:
            1. Create a new node
            2. Set its `next` to the current head
            3. Set its `prev` to NULL
            4. Update old head's `prev`
            5. Update head pointer
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Insertion at the End

            Steps:
            1. Create a new node
            2. Traverse to the last node
            3. Set last node’s `next` to new node
            4. Set new node’s `prev` to last node
            5. Set new node’s `next` to NULL
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Deletion

            To delete a node:
            - Update the **next** pointer of the previous node
            - Update the **prev** pointer of the next node

            No shifting of elements is required.
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Time Complexity

            | Operation | Complexity |
            |---------|------------|
            | Access | O(n) |
            | Insert (known node) | O(1) |
            | Delete (known node) | O(1) |
            | Search | O(n) |

            Traversal still costs linear time.
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Advantages

            - Bidirectional traversal
            - Easier deletion than singly linked lists
            - Useful for complex navigation structures

            Trade-off: extra memory usage.
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Disadvantages

            - Extra memory for `prev` pointer
            - More pointer updates → higher chance of bugs
            - Slightly more complex implementation

            Choose wisely based on use case.
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise — Doubly Linked List

            In this exercise, you will **implement a doubly linked list in Python** from scratch.

            A **doubly linked list** is a linear data structure where:
            - Each node stores **data**
            - Each node has a reference to the **next node**
            - Each node has a reference to the **previous node**

            This allows traversal in **both directions**.

            ## Structure Overview

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              Null1[None] --> Node1;
              Node1 --> Node2;
              Node2 --> Node3;
              Node3 --> Null2[None];

              Node2 -.-> Node1;
              Node3 -.-> Node2;
            /mermaid

            ## Task

            Implement a doubly linked list that supports the following operations:

            1. Create a `Node` class  
            2. Create a `DoublyLinkedList` class  
            3. Insert a value at the **end** of the list  
            4. Display the list **from head to tail**  

            ## Steps to Follow

            1. Define a `Node` class with:
              - `data`
              - `next`
              - `prev`
            2. Define a `DoublyLinkedList` class with:
              - a `head` pointer
            3. Implement an `append(value)` method
            4. Implement a `print_forward()` method
            5. Test your implementation

            spoiler
            ```
            class Node:
                def __init__(self, data):
                    self.data = data
                    self.next = None
                    self.prev = None


            class DoublyLinkedList:
                def __init__(self):
                    self.head = None

                def append(self, value):
                    new_node = Node(value)

                    if self.head is None:
                        self.head = new_node
                        return

                    current = self.head
                    while current.next:
                        current = current.next

                    current.next = new_node
                    new_node.prev = current

                def print_forward(self):
                    current = self.head
                    while current:
                        print(current.data, end=" <-> ")
                        current = current.next
                    print("None")


            # Example usage
            lst = DoublyLinkedList()
            lst.append(10)
            lst.append(20)
            lst.append(30)

            lst.print_forward()
            /spoiler
            </script>
